Trends in travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, the ČSSR had only five approved public travel agencies: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
At the time, the travel agencies sold mainly travels to the socialist Eastern Bloc countries, and in the West they were only allowed to choose.
And so Czech tourists traveled to the Baltic Sea (in the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the Crimean Peninsula on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea and to Hungary to the Balaton.
A slight exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when one was also allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia took a pro-Western course and therefore travel to Yugoslavia was severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that even citizens of the Eastern Bloc (also the Czechoslovakians) were not allowed to travel freely within the framework of the socialist countries.
If, for example, a citizen of the ČSSR wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, he needed a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual trips were not possible.
Even then the travel agencies also offered travel to the West, but then you had to buy huge snakes or stay in the sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
Even so, things had not gone well yet.
The so-called foreign exchange promise - the condition for a trip to the West - was granted only "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so without a foreign exchange commitment it would have been impossible to raise the necessary financial resources (Western currency) for a trip to the West.
Therefore, most Czechs spent their vacation in the country, no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and dats - a habit that continues to this day.
The whole revolution of 1989 followed a travel revolution of the Czechs.
While a holiday in the GDR or Bulgaria was the measure of all things by 1989, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their holidays abroad in countries around the world.
A huge paradox, which one is no longer aware of today, is the fact that one could not travel to the most popular holiday country of the Czech - Croatia until 1989 because it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
Right from the beginning of the 1990s, the foreign exchange obligation was abolished in the neighbouring Western European countries, which caused an enormous wave of short visits, especially to Vienna in Austria and Germany.
The Czechoslovakians simply couldn't get enough of their travels to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to have been there for at least a few days.
So the Czech vacationers slept on trips to Paris in the tent in the park, because who would have had the money for accommodation in the hotel or in a pension at the time.
A typical feature of travel abroad from the Czech Republic was a fully packed trunk with canned, beer and permanent sausage, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech crown - after decades our tourists were finally able to buy the Western currency freely.
Our level of living and thus the average salaries increased, resulting in another important moment in 1997.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, the travel agencies began to prepare regular trips through charter flights after 1997, making the flight possible to negotiate quantity discounts incredibly cheaper compared to the past.
At the end of the 1990s, with the exception of the USA, the Czechs had already had foreign exchange-free payments with all the developed countries of the world, making travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post office" travel came in 2000, when thanks to the high demand of the first direct charter flight to an exotic country - to Thailand.
Since then, every year direct charter aircraft fly with Czech passengers in far away sunny countries; this year, twelve exotic destinations are flyn directly from the Czech Republic.
To the 100th Tsd. Czechs travel every year in exotic countries!
Another significant moment in the era that marked our "post-revolutionary" development came in 2008.
On November 17th, 2008, the United States lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, which definitely included our country among the highly developed countries of the world.
In 2008, the Czechs spent more than half of their holiday abroad (50.3%) for the first time in their history, spending more than 15 thousand CZK per head on a single holiday stay, including the cost of the holiday destination.
