To this end, the President of the Consejo General del Instituto Electoral de Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, reminded us that just last November, the electoral body had adopted a series of rules on the harmonisation of local rules with the reforms of the states in electoral matters.
It should be recalled that Michoacán had not adapted either his political constitution or his election law or his law on election justice to the reforms adopted by the Congress, so that they had not entered into force during this election round. Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel avoided their publication in the State Advertiser within the specified time limits with the argument, nor had any objections to it.
On 9 November, the Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) decided on the constitutional action filed by the local legislative and judged the State representative's vote on the constitutional reforms as "ineffective and unlawful", since it has no right to "decision or veto against it".
María de los Ángeles Llanderal explained in an interview on the possibility of individual counting the votes, that, thanks to the adoption of the guidelines by the Consejo General del IEM, there is now the possibility that the local electoral authority can count the voting notes in part or in full.
Thus, the votes contained in one or more election packages may be partially counted under the following conditions.The results in the minutes do not agree; the minutes on the counting and calculation of votes are not available in writing or are not in the possession of the chairman of the electoral committee or there are obvious errors or amendments in the minutes.
In addition, the total number of full-filled voting tickets can be counted if there is a difference between the alleged winner and the one in second place, which is equal to or less than one percent, provided that at the beginning of the meeting there is an explicit request from the party or coalition chairman, who is the second of the above-mentioned candidates.
The votes may also be counted in their entirety if, after completion of the ordinary calculation, it is established that the difference between the alleged winner and the candidate in second place is equal or less than one percent, provided that there is an explicit request from a representative of the party whose candidate has become second. In this case, the voting packages which were suspended in partial counting would be excluded.
It is worth mentioning that the elections in Morelia are in the same situation where, according to PREP, the difference between the first and the second place is almost 0.16 percent, although the votes of 129 out of a total of 923 voting protocols have not yet been counted.
