Who influenced you as a bass player?
From so many+
One of the first to come to mind is Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could talk all afternoon about the bass players I like.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep the grunge alive, although it is no longer a fashion phenomenon?
I think we all don't feel very connected to the word grunge.
When I think about it, I think of the bands I mentioned before, such as Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the others who came up at the same time. If they are still important today, I think it's great because it's worth listening to this music and bands like Mudhoney are doing better music now than ever before.
At first, her music was darker, now she's more positive.
Why?
This is interesting, because I think there are a few songs on the new album that could work a little lightly. But there are also other songs like The End or Just Breath that are classified as very dark songs, although they also have something positive in themselves.
The tears came to me when I heard Ed playing them. They are very dark songs.
I believe that when you get older and something tragic happened in your life - e.g. if you lose a family member or a friend - that influences your artistic work and your music and these two songs clearly embody it for me.
But I also believe that you can be a happy person and still make dark music.
