Visible flight:
In accordance with the flight standards, this was a flight in accordance with the rules of the visual flight. This means that the crew must have had sufficient visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
The AICM recorded appropriate weather conditions at takeoff. During the next flight towards the border area between Mexico City and the Mexico State, some deep clouds pulled up.
Selected flight routes:
It is possible that the team had chosen a lower area with a better view towards the Cuernavaca valley because of the clouds.
Hit-up point:
The impact coordinates and the last radar recording of the helicopter agree. There may not have been any loss of control over the aircraft or a deviation from the flight route before the impact.
Scattering the remains of the aircraft in a limited area:
The information available until now indicates that the helicopter was impacted from a straight and lateral direction.
The pattern of the scattered aircraft remains suggests that the helicopter with its unscathed structure was impacted on the ground.
No evidence of fire or explosion:
The remains of the aircraft offer neither fire nor explosion at the site of the accident.
The latest findings indicate several soil contacts.
In the on-site investigations, aircraft parts were found at a height of 9200 feet above sea level. The terrain is abject and has an angle of seven to thirty degrees.
The photos show the sequence in which the helicopter was probably broken.
Some information suggests that the helicopter could have had several ground contacts.
