Asphalt from the UNAM prevents impact holes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at the Mexican University UNAM, develops modified asphalt with polymers to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
It would not be necessary to repair nearly 200,000 pits if the rainy season in the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (City Area of the Valley of Mexico) broke out, said Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at the University of UNAM, warning and assured that if the design and maintenance of the asphalty floor were properly seen, the number of holes would be significantly reduced or even completely avoided.
In his lecture "Technical Gaps", which he gave on the occasion of the International Year on Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible is developing asphalt modified with polymers to produce a mixture similar to the asphalt, but which has greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera said that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climates, such as in some cities in the north of the country, to improve the behavior of the street floor and thus avoid the occurrence of impact holes.
He explained that the asphalt - the heaviest part of the oil - is a hydrocarbon compound, some of which have a high molecular weight - the so-called asphales - and the other part a low one - the so-called malthenes. Together they give the street floor its characteristic toughness behavior.
The toughness of the asphalt means that it behaves like a liquid at high temperatures of almost 180°C, at 120°C it is very tough and almost solid at 50°C, while it breaks at very low temperatures.
"This means that the resilience of the asphalt on the roads is not uniform, but changes in one day depending on the weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," said the chemical engineer.
The researcher of the FQ noted that the streets of Mexico City had mostly a flexible street flooring composed of six layers of materials, the last three of which included asphalt.
Between the top layers lies a wear layer made of asphalt, which is made of small, asphalt-washed stones and then solidified.
Every single stone of this wear layer had been bathed in asphalt.
When the vehicles move on and forces are generated, this layer allows a good distribution of forces in the street floor.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would spread even better," said the chemical engineer.
"On the wear layer," he said, "is designed a final layer, the so-called supporting layer, which is made of tiny stones, i.e. sand, which was also bathed in asphalt.
As this layer is in contact with the vehicle tyres, they need a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and they have to produce friction.
Moreover, that which receives and distributes most of the forces in this street floor also requires an appropriate thickness and the material it consists of must be maintained.
The weather conditions, in particular humidity and temperature fluctuations, are other important factors to consider, above all the water," he said, "because it significantly affects the behaviour of the wear layer.
When the terrain gets wet, water penetrates into the layer and only comes out difficult. This causes a softening of all layers of the street floor and, as a result, the appearance of impact holes.
When a impact hole is created," he said, "the cover layer will be removed first, while the wear layer will only be affected after that. But the damage does not arise immediately, but it is a process that would have to be maintained during the first signs by appropriate maintenance programs."
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (National Research System of Mexico) stated that the vehicle load is another important cause for the occurrence of impact holes. Therefore, the thickness of each layer of the road covering must always be in relation to the vehicle load and it must be ensured that this regulation is complied with in order to avoid frequent impact holes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that a lot of research was still pending, for example about asphalt emulsions that were already on the market in other countries, and with which the impact holes could be repaired simply and without application high temperatures.
