German chancellor Angelika Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his colleague Mark Rutte from the Netherlands have symbolically turned the control of the valve, which carries the Russian gas into the Western European network.
With the new gas pipeline, 27.5 billion cubic meters of additional Russian gas per year will be delivered to Western Europe by a first pipeline of 1.224 km long that connects the region of St Petersburg with Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
A second pipeline allowing a total supply of 55 billion cubic metres of gas - the equivalent of French total consumption - will be completed by the end of 2012.
And one already lets the possibility of building a third line sound on its own track.
For Gazprom, the timely and precise completion of this huge building looks like a victory.
The project was highly controversial in Poland and the Baltic States.
