All of this explains the broad smile of the numerous Gazprom managers represented in Lubmin regarding the gas supply.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also an outstanding technique.
The underwater line consists of steel with concrete coating to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the bottom of the sea, about 200 m deep.
In their construction, minefields dating from World War II had to be eroded.
"Approximately hundreds of mines had to be removed or destroyed with caution," said Jens Müller, spokesman for the Nord Stream company.
In addition, increased measures had to be taken to protect fauna and flora.
The line is a long metal snake, heavy as 242 Eiffel Towers, which is not interrupted throughout the length: neither through valves nor maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but the project managers have distanced themselves from it, since the Sweden had little desire to see a Russian state company settled in a permanent manner at the level of its coasts.
"In the case of a hawk, we close the gas throughput in less than a minute," Jens Müller explained.
In the case of a leak, the gas contained in the gas pipeline escapes into the air.
However, this case is considered by the constructors as little likely, since the welding of the welding is estimated to be one leak per 100,000 years.
State monitoring of the gas transmission is ensured by an underwater robot controlled for external observation purposes from a seaship, as well as by a device circulating inside the gas transmission.
It has the shape of a cigar, measures a meter diameter, is introduced into the interior of the pipeline and moved through the gas pressure.
After three full days of moving through the line at a speed of 3 meters per second, the device provides the most accurate information on any deformities of the metal upon arrival.
The gas transmission was designed to work for fifty years without even having to undergo the slightest repair.
Gas circulation is simply guaranteed by pressure.
This is 200 bar at the entrance, 100 bar at the exit point.
Five societies have united their forces to achieve this project.
However, the management remains in the hands of Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
Furthermore, the German companies E. ON and BASF are affiliated here (each 15.5%), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (each at 9%).
These five companies have formed a company community called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the gas pipeline.
It has its seat in Zug in Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased the entire capacity of its gas transport to renewable twenty-year contract.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, no matter how large the volume of gas actually transported is, Jens Müller specified.
The financing of gas transmission was secured to 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
Total labour costs should amount to 7.4 billion euros for both pipelines.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
However, minority shareholders are able to recover their expenses, as Gazprom alone bears the risk of liability.
